{META_DATA}: THE DEPARTED
{META_DATA}: Written by
{META_DATA}: William Monahan
{META_DATA}: Based on Infernal Affairs
{META_DATA}: SCRIPT AS SHOT COMPILED SEPTEMBER 2006
{META_DATA}: FADE UP ON
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: THE SOUTH BOSTON HOUSING PROJECTS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A MAZE OF BUILDINGS AGAINST THE HARBOR.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COSTELLO (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: I don't want to be a product of my environment.
{DIALOGUE}: I want my environment to be a product...of me.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: YELLOW RIPPLES PAST THE CAMERA AND WHEN IT CLEARS WE SEE THROUGH DIESEL SMOKE: A BUSING PROTEST IN PROGRESS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: THE SCHOOL-BUS, FULL OF BLACK KIDS, IS HIT WITH BRICKS, ROCKS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: N.B.: (THIS IS NOT SETTING THE LIVE ACTION IN 1974; IT IS A HISTORICAL MONTAGE, THE BACKGROUND FOR COSTELLO'S V.O.).
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. THE AUTOBODY SHOP. DAY.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: COSTELLO's profile passes in a dark room.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COSTELLO (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Years ago, we had the Church.
{DIALOGUE}: That was only a way of saying we had each other.
{DIALOGUE}: The Knights of Columbus were head-breakers.
{DIALOGUE}: They took over their piece of the city.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. SOUTHIE. VARIOUS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The neighborhood.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 1980's.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We won't be here long.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This isn't where Costello ends up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's where he began.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Liquor stores with shamrocked signs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEN FISHING near Castle Island.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Catholic SCHOOLKIDS playing in an asphalted schoolyard.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COSTELLO (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Twenty years after an Irishman couldn't get a job, we had the presidency.
{DIALOGUE}: That's what the niggers don't realize.
{DIALOGUE}: If I got one thing against the black chaps it's this.
{DIALOGUE}: No one gives it to you.
{DIALOGUE}: You have to take it.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. LUNCH COUNTER. DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: COSTELLO comes in.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The shop is one that sells papers, sundries, fountain drinks...and fronts a bookie operation.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: YOUNG COSTELLO
{META_DATA}: (leaning over cluttered counter)
{DIALOGUE}: Don't make me have to come down here again.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 2.
{META_DATA}: CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PROPRIETOR
{DIALOGUE}: Won't happen again, Mr. C.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The frightened proprietor hands over money.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Fifty bucks, a hundred, doesn't matter.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: COSTELLO is never the threatener.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His demeanor is gentle, philosophical.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Almost a shrink's probing bedside manner.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He has great interest in the world as he moves through it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As if he originally came from a different world and his survival in this one depends on close continual observation and analysis.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: YOUNG COLIN looks up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE ON his eyes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is fourteen or fifteen, but small for his age.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bookish.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: COSTELLO eyes the proprietor's TEENAGE DAUGHTER, working behind the counter.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He takes a propane lighter, and, strangely, pays for it (the proprietor startled) and waits for change.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He lights a MORE cigarette with the lighter.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: YOUNG COSTELLO
{DIALOGUE}: Carmen's developing into a fine young lady.
{DIALOGUE}: You should be proud.
{DIALOGUE}: You get your period yet, Carmen?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The PROPRIETOR is uneasy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: COSTELLO turns to YOUNG COLIN (about 14) staring at the local hero.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Costello reaches up above and behind the counter and takes down some cigarettes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: YOUNG COSTELLO (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: You Johnny Sullivan's kid?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: COLIN nods.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: YOUNG COSTELLO (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: You live with your grandmother?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: COLIN nods.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: YOUNG COLIN
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
